defaultT
defaulthe public interest in relation to postal services
default4.2
default              
defaultThe public inte
defaultrest can be best served by ensuring the provision of postal services (including universal postal services) which are reliable, cost efficient and of high quality.   Postal services provide a vital delivery infrastructure for the economy in respect of commu
defaultnications and, increasingly, as a means of low cost distribution of e-commerce.  Lower costs and greater efficiency in postal services benefit the wider economy, in particular in
default reducing costs for businesses and
default stimulating the development of 
defaulte
default commerce. 
default    
defaultPrivatisation and postal services
default4.3
default              
defaultGlobally, universal postal services are usually provided by national posts in the public sector.  In the EU, which has moved most quickly to reform the sector, there has been only a gradual and cautious move to privatize national posts, with successful and
default efficient national posts operating both within and outside the public sector.  It is therefore counter-intuitive to state that privatization is essential to ensure postal services, which implies that postal services may soon fail across most of the world.
default 
defaultNationa
default              
defaultl posts and financial performance
default4.4
default              
defaultIn practice national posts remain in a fairly cossetted or insulated financial situation compared to most businesses, revenues are largely safeguarded going forward (mail volume declines offset by a changing 
defaultvolume composition and by e-commerce traffic growth) and costs are set through wage level choices and also the pace of achievement of efficiency gains.  Although most national posts have not pursued profit maximization strategies, (which renders internatio
defaultnal benchmarking less useful) margins can be significantly increased both through raising prices (where the national  post retains market power) and/or becoming more cost efficient by reducing headcount, making costs more flexible or restraining wages.    
defaultWhere national posts have been privatized they have made significant returns in letters products through increased prices and through a process of cost reduction which remains ongoing.  
default&#xa0;
defaultRoyal Mail’s position in the UK as the universal service provider 
default4.
default5
default              
defaultRoyal Mail as the traditional provider of the universal postal service enjoys a legacy of significant market power in the delivery of postal items, particularly in respect of letters and low weight standard parcels.
default  
defaultThe profitability or otherwise of its
default universal service provision as a whole is determined by the level of postal volumes, the level of wage costs at Royal Mail, technical efficiency at the business and the level of its prices.  Increases for example in wages will apparently increase the “net
default costs of the universal service”, whereas greater cost efficiency or price rises will reduce it.  
defaultFuture demand for postal delivery
default4.6
default              
defaultUsage of the postal delivery network has changed over time with traditional communications products declining but being
default replaced by advertising (direct) mail and now by e commerce traffic.  Whilst postal providers such as Royal Mail have found it difficult to innovate and
default have
default regularly predict
defaulted
default the imminent end of their business, dynamism in the wider economy has continu
defaulted to find an outlet in the universal postal delivery network, which retains economies of scope and scale which offset its relative technical and cost inefficiency.  Royal Mail enjoys around 40% of the e commerce delivery market
default,
default with many
default other
default companies
default 
defaultalso
default delivering to the door every week
default.  First mover advantage in this market represents a significant commercial opportunity going forward.  
default 
