default4.23
default              
defaultIn light of current valuations, clearly the market has taken the view that although there are risks, they are offset by the commercial opportunities available to the company both to inc
defaultrease margins in its traditional letters delivery and to grow revenues in e commerce delivery.  For example were mail volumes to decline more rapidly, then the business could increase the pace of its efficiency improvements or raise prices more steeply.  
default4.24
default              
defaultFurther, our analysis 
defaultdid not take account
default of the effects of such steep price rises at Royal Mail as have occurred over the last couple of years, though we did assume that the business would at least get a return on the capital investment made.    
defaultWh
defaulty was the company so undervalued? 
default4.25
default              
defaultIn light of the above how then can the undervaluation of the business be explained, even 
defaultconsidering that the government would have wished to attract investors?
defaultThe argumentation for the sale
default4.26
default              
defaultIn part the origins
default of the undervaluation lie in the Hooper Report which presented an over-gloomy view   of postal market development, focusing on negative market trends (electronic substitution of letters exacerbated by economic downturn) and financial problems at Royal Mai
defaultl rather than looking at the market as a whole.  
defaultThe results of this led to a strange argumentation for the sale which ran along the lines of “this business is falling apart and soon to die…please buy it.”
default4.27
default              
defaultWhilst this may have been seen as politically
default necessary it was a very weak starting point for a negotiations with city investors and, it can be argued that this by itself may have been a cause of undervaluation.
default&#xa0;
defaultRegulatory capture
default4.28
default              
defaultThe undervaluation also reflects weaknesses in the manner that BI
defaultS has handled its stewardship of the postal industry.   This has included a tendency to become captured by Royal Mail’s view of the postal business and to place too high a priority on short term political risks for Ministers (in relation to concerns over p
defaultostal strikes or service failures).  
default4.29
default              
defaultDuring the process of the sale Postcomm and Consumer Focus, which represented customer and consumer interests and provided an independent perspective were both scrapped and a more light touch regulatory regime put
default in place.
default4.30
default              
defaultFaced with this legacy of unbalanced argumentation about the potential for rapid decline of the business and with a departmental advice which reflected a very cautious view of the prospects for the business, it was difficult for Ministers t
defaulto take a more objective view of its potential for commercial success.
defaultLack of alternative voices in the process of the sale 
default    
default4.31
default              
defaultMinisters went down a conventional route in seeking advice on the valuation
default asking Investment banks who knew little about the postal sector and about Royal Mail in particular.  This was reflected in the wide valuations. Faced with suggestions that Royal Mail may be worth much more money, advisors and Ministers, 
defaultunsurprisingly vie
defaultwed any dissenting valuation (compared to over-negative ones) with skepticism.  
defaultIn practice an objective view was only likely to come from outside BIS and
default from the enthusiasm of buyers
default during the process of the float.
default  However, e
defaultven when faced with clear e
defaultvidence of over subscription of the sale,
default Ministers could not believe that previous advice was incorrect and
default seeing the political risks of a failed sale
default continued to undervalue the business.
default           
defaultGaming strategies during the process of the sale
default4.32
default              
defaultIt is also likely that the government’s attempt to tilt the ownership of the business towards long term and passive investor led it towards undervaluation.  
